; preludes: form-stdlib/core.fk form-stdlib/sha256.fk
;
; decidable-channel.fk — STONE 46. A channel on which silence is impossible.
;
; ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
; WHY THIS EXISTS
;
; Three failures in one day were one defect at three altitudes:
;   * a Metal buffer never written read back as a computed zero;
;   * fkwu read a file cut mid-write and answered 3 for `(do (add 1 2)` — a right
;     computation of the wrong text;
;   * eight subagents ended and the only signal was the ABSENCE of a completion
;     record, so a clean finish, a timeout and a kill were indistinguishable.
;
; In each case a close carried no evidence of why it closed, and an absence was
; read as a value. This file is the protocol layer that makes that impossible.
;
; ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
; THE GROUNDING — this is a theorem, not an invention
;
; axioms/core-axioms.form:51
;   axiom-3-content-addressing
;     "a cell's identity is computed from its present composition; same
;      composition is the same cell"
;   axioms/core-axioms.form:57  (generates … reversibility-of-the-referenced
;                                names-are-free-query-keys honesty-is-cheap)
;
;   Identity is content. So "did you receive what I sent?" is answered by
;   COMPARING NODE-IDS — from either end, at any time, with no ordering, no
;   timestamps, no sequence numbers. Order-independence is not a feature added
;   here; it is what axiom-3 already says. `names-are-free-query-keys` is
;   literally the resolver below: a digest is a free query key.
;
; axioms/core-axioms.form:59-62
;   axiom-4-boundary
;     "… passage not through the offered interface is breach, and breach is
;      observable"
;   The frame header (magic + declared length + declared digest) IS the offered
;   interface. Bytes that did not pass through it are refused AS SUCH — state
;   DC-NOT-A-FRAME — rather than mis-read as a shorter message. Breach is
;   observable because the refusal has its own name.
;
; axioms/core-axioms.form:64-66
;   axiom-5-offer
;     "to run a cell and to speak to a cell are one act: offer a cell with
;      0..many arg-cells; it is acknowledged by exactly one of nothing, 0, 1,
;      node"
;   (ack-values-are (axiom-1-states + node))
;   The ack vocabulary here is EXACTLY those four and no more. And per
;   axioms/core-axioms.form:37 (axiom-1: "nothing-is-first-class
;   the-ground-not-a-missing-0"), `nothing` is a STATE that was SENT, not the
;   absence of a send. That distinction is this whole stone.
;
; ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
; TWINBLIND (868) — WHAT IS CANONICAL AND WHAT IS CHOSEN
;
; CANONICAL (self-checking; a hash either matches or it does not):
;   * A body's identity is sha256(body). Nothing here can choose that; the
;     digest is computed from the present composition, axiom-3 exactly.
;   * Whether a frame is complete: the declared length and declared digest
;     either agree with the bytes present, or they do not. No judgement.
;   * Whether an ack names an offer: two 32-byte digests are equal or they are
;     not.
;
; CHOSEN (stated here so the choice is a record, not a preference):
;   * WHAT COUNTS AS A COMPLETE MESSAGE. Chosen: magic present, the full
;     38-byte header present, exactly the declared number of body bytes
;     present, and sha256(body) equal to the declared digest. Justified from
;     axiom-4: the header IS the offered interface, so a frame is complete when
;     it has fully crossed that interface and not before. Length is declared
;     BEFORE the body so that a cut mid-write is short against a promise
;     already made — the promise is what makes the absence decidable.
;   * THE ACK VOCABULARY. Chosen: exactly nothing/0/1/node, tagged 0/1/2/3.
;     Justified from axiom-5's "exactly one of nothing, 0, 1, node" — the
;     protocol may not add a fifth value, and may not drop `nothing`.
;   * THE ABSENT AND CONFLICT CODES. Chosen: the resolver answers -1 for ABSENT
;     and -2 for CONFLICT, disjoint from the four ack tags 0..3. Justified from
;     axiom-1's nothing-is-first-class: if ABSENT shared a code with `nothing`
;     the protocol would re-commit the very defect it exists to end.
;   * REFUSING RATHER THAN RESOLVING A CONFLICT. Chosen: two valid acks naming
;     one digest with different values answer CONFLICT in every ordering, rather
;     than last-one-wins. Justified from axiom-3: identity is the present
;     composition, and position is not composition — so a rule that let position
;     decide would make the answer order-dependent, contradicting the axiom the
;     protocol is derived from. Refusal is the only order-free resolution.
;
; ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
; WIRE FORMAT
;
;   frame = MAGIC(2) || LEN(4, big-endian) || DIGEST(32) || BODY(LEN)
;   MAGIC = 70 75   ("F" "K")
;   DIGEST = sha256(BODY)
;   header length = 38
;
; Bytes are carried as INT values 0..255 throughout — never as string bytes.
; (wraithcarry, corpus 864: the body cannot build a byte-exact string of a byte
; >= 128, so a digest that lived in a string would be silently wrong.)
;
;   body of an OFFER  = 79 || payload…                    ; 79 = "O"
;   body of an ACK    = 65 || value-tag || target-digest(32) [|| node-digest(32)]
;   body of a CLOSE   = 67 || reason || last-digest(32)   ; 67 = "C"
;
; The OFFER's node-id is sha256 of its body — which is exactly the digest its
; own frame already declares. So the ack names a number both ends can compute
; independently, at any time, with no shared clock.
; ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

(do

  ; ── constants as nullary defns ───────────────────────────────────────────────
  ; (fkwu's defn frames cannot read an enclosing do-let — see receipts/
  ; 2026-07-22-fkwu-silent-green.md D3 — so every constant is a call, never a
  ; free name.)
  (defn dc-magic0 () 70)                  ; "F"
  (defn dc-magic1 () 75)                  ; "K"
  (defn dc-header-len () 38)              ; 2 magic + 4 length + 32 digest

  ; frame states. Every not-a-message state is NEGATIVE and distinct, so no
  ; failure can ever be read as the value 0 or 1 (edgedrop / zerobirth).
  (defn dc-complete () 2)                 ; the whole message crossed the interface
  (defn dc-short-header () -1)            ; cut before the promise was even made
  (defn dc-short-body () -2)              ; the promise was made and not kept — cut mid-write
  (defn dc-digest-mismatch () -3)         ; right length, wrong content
  (defn dc-not-a-frame () -4)             ; never passed through the interface — axiom-4 breach
  (defn dc-overlong () -5)                ; more bytes than declared

  ; body tags
  (defn dc-tag-offer () 79)               ; "O"
  (defn dc-tag-ack () 65)                 ; "A"
  (defn dc-tag-close () 67)               ; "C"

  ; the ack vocabulary — axiom-5's four, and only those four
  (defn dc-ack-nothing () 0)
  (defn dc-ack-zero () 1)
  (defn dc-ack-one () 2)
  (defn dc-ack-node () 3)

  ; resolver answers, disjoint from 0..3 above
  (defn dc-absent () -1)                  ; no ack for this digest exists at all
  (defn dc-conflict () -2)                ; two valid acks disagree about this digest

  ; close reasons — a close carries evidence of WHY it closed (hushend)
  (defn dc-close-done () 1)               ; the work finished
  (defn dc-close-handover () 2)           ; handed to another cell
  (defn dc-close-offline () 3)            ; going offline on purpose

  ; transcript end kinds
  (defn dc-end-closed () 3)               ; ends with a valid CLOSE naming a digest
  (defn dc-end-stopped () -6)             ; ends with valid frames but no CLOSE — it just stopped
  (defn dc-end-cut () -7)                 ; ends mid-frame — the stream was cut

  ; ── byte helpers ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  ; dc-u32-be — a 4-byte big-endian length. Pure arithmetic; no bit-ops needed,
  ; so this reads identically on every kernel arm.
  (defn dc-u32-be (n)
    (list (mod (div n 16777216) 256)
          (mod (div n 65536) 256)
          (mod (div n 256) 256)
          (mod n 256)))

  (defn dc-be-u32 (b0 b1 b2 b3)
    (add (mul b0 16777216) (add (mul b1 65536) (add (mul b2 256) b3))))

  ; dc-bytes-eq — list equality over ints. The whole protocol's comparison
  ; primitive: this is what "same composition is the same cell" becomes in
  ; running code.
  (defn dc-bytes-eq (a b)
    (if (eq (len a) 0) (if (eq (len b) 0) 1 0)
      (if (eq (len b) 0) 0
        (if (eq (head a) (head b)) (dc-bytes-eq (tail a) (tail b)) 0))))

  ; ── the node-id of a body ────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  ; dc-digest — the identity of a body. axiom-3: computed from its present
  ; composition, nothing else. 32 ints.
  (defn dc-digest (body) (sha256 body))

  ; dc-nodeid-of-digest — the body's OWN content-address constructor over the
  ; first 16 digest bytes: four uint32 words -> (make_nodeid pkg level type inst).
  ; This is the bridge from the wire digest to the kernel's node identity, so
  ; "does an ack for node X exist?" can be asked with node_eq as well as with
  ; dc-bytes-eq.
  (defn dc-nodeid-of-digest (d)
    (make_nodeid (dc-be-u32 (nth d 0) (nth d 1) (nth d 2) (nth d 3))
                 (dc-be-u32 (nth d 4) (nth d 5) (nth d 6) (nth d 7))
                 (dc-be-u32 (nth d 8) (nth d 9) (nth d 10) (nth d 11))
                 (dc-be-u32 (nth d 12) (nth d 13) (nth d 14) (nth d 15))))

  (defn dc-nodeid-of-body (body) (dc-nodeid-of-digest (dc-digest body)))

  ; ── framing ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  ; dc-frame — wrap a body as a complete frame. The length is declared BEFORE
  ; the body: that declaration is what makes a later cut decidable.
  (defn dc-frame (body)
    (append (list (dc-magic0) (dc-magic1))
            (append (dc-u32-be (len body))
                    (append (dc-digest body) body))))

  ; dc-frame-declared-len — the length the frame PROMISED. Meaningful only when
  ; at least 6 bytes are present; callers reach it through dc-frame-state.
  (defn dc-frame-declared-len (f)
    (dc-be-u32 (nth f 2) (nth f 3) (nth f 4) (nth f 5)))

  (defn dc-frame-declared-digest (f) (take 32 (drop 6 f)))

  (defn dc-frame-body (f) (drop (dc-header-len) f))

  ; dc-frame-state — THE decision. Answers exactly one of the six states above.
  ; A frame is a message only when it answers dc-complete.
  ;
  ; The ordering of the tests matters and is deliberate:
  ;   magic first  — a byte run that never crossed the interface is named as
  ;                  breach (axiom-4) and never gets a length reading;
  ;   header next  — a cut before the promise is a different failure from a cut
  ;                  after it, and conflating them is the hushend defect;
  ;   length next  — short-body is the cut-mid-write case: the frame promised N
  ;                  and delivered fewer, so the shortfall is arithmetic, not
  ;                  a guess;
  ;   digest last  — only reached when the byte count is exactly right, so a
  ;                  digest mismatch means content corruption specifically.
  (defn dc-frame-state (f)
    (if (lt (len f) 2) (dc-short-header)
      (if (eq (dc-bytes-eq (take 2 f) (list (dc-magic0) (dc-magic1))) 0) (dc-not-a-frame)
        (if (lt (len f) (dc-header-len)) (dc-short-header)
          (if (lt (len f) (add (dc-header-len) (dc-frame-declared-len f))) (dc-short-body)
            (if (gt (len f) (add (dc-header-len) (dc-frame-declared-len f))) (dc-overlong)
              (if (eq (dc-bytes-eq (dc-digest (dc-frame-body f)) (dc-frame-declared-digest f)) 0)
                  (dc-digest-mismatch)
                  (dc-complete))))))))

  (defn dc-frame-complete? (f) (if (eq (dc-frame-state f) (dc-complete)) 1 0))

  ; ── offers, acks, closes ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────

  (defn dc-offer (payload) (dc-frame (cons (dc-tag-offer) payload)))

  ; dc-offer-nodeid-bytes — the digest a receiver must name back. It is exactly
  ; the digest the offer frame already declares, so BOTH ends compute it from
  ; the same bytes and neither has to be told it.
  (defn dc-offer-nodeid-bytes (offer-frame) (dc-frame-declared-digest offer-frame))

  ; dc-ack — an acknowledgement NAMING the digest it answers. value-tag is one
  ; of the four; node-digest is the 32 bytes for dc-ack-node and (empty) for the
  ; three terminal values.
  (defn dc-ack (target-digest value-tag node-digest)
    (dc-frame (append (list (dc-tag-ack) value-tag)
                      (append target-digest node-digest))))

  ; dc-ack-nothing-frame — the sentence this stone exists for. "I received it
  ; and I have nothing." It is a SENT ack whose value is `nothing`, which is why
  ; it can never be confused with an ack that was never sent.
  (defn dc-ack-nothing-frame (target-digest)
    (dc-ack target-digest (dc-ack-nothing) (empty)))

  (defn dc-close (reason last-digest)
    (dc-frame (append (list (dc-tag-close) reason) last-digest)))

  ; ── reading a validated frame ────────────────────────────────────────────────

  (defn dc-body-tag (f) (head (dc-frame-body f)))

  (defn dc-ack-value-tag (f) (nth (dc-frame-body f) 1))

  (defn dc-ack-target (f) (take 32 (drop 2 (dc-frame-body f))))

  (defn dc-ack-node-digest (f) (take 32 (drop 34 (dc-frame-body f))))

  (defn dc-close-reason (f) (nth (dc-frame-body f) 1))

  (defn dc-close-last (f) (take 32 (drop 2 (dc-frame-body f))))

  ; is this VALIDATED frame an ack naming `d`?
  (defn dc-ack-names? (f d)
    (if (eq (dc-frame-complete? f) 0) 0
      (if (eq (dc-body-tag f) (dc-tag-ack))
          (dc-bytes-eq (dc-ack-target f) d)
          0)))

  ; ── the resolver — "does an ack for node X exist?" ───────────────────────────
  ;
  ; A total function. It never waits, never blocks, and never answers by the
  ; passage of time. It answers one of:
  ;   -1 ABSENT    — no valid ack in this transcript names that digest
  ;    0 NOTHING   — an ack was SENT whose value is `nothing`
  ;    1 ZERO      — an ack was sent whose value is 0
  ;    2 ONE       — an ack was sent whose value is 1
  ;    3 NODE      — an ack was sent naming a node
  ;   -2 CONFLICT  — two valid acks name that digest with different values
  ;
  ; ABSENT (-1) and NOTHING (0) are different numbers. That is the theorem in
  ; one line: an unsent ack and an ack of `nothing` are decidably different.
  ;
  ; ORDER-FREEDOM. The fold below reads the transcript in whatever order it is
  ; handed. Its only order-sensitive step would be "a later ack replaces an
  ; earlier one" — so there is no such step. A second ack that AGREES is
  ; absorbed (content-addressing: the same composition is the same cell, so a
  ; duplicate carries no new information); a second ack that DISAGREES latches
  ; CONFLICT, and CONFLICT absorbs everything after it. Both absorption rules
  ; are commutative and idempotent, which is exactly what makes the fold
  ; independent of order.
  (defn dc-resolve-step (acc f d)
    (if (eq (dc-ack-names? f d) 0) acc
      (if (eq acc (dc-conflict)) (dc-conflict)
        (if (eq acc (dc-absent)) (dc-ack-value-tag f)
          (if (eq acc (dc-ack-value-tag f)) acc (dc-conflict))))))

  (defn dc-resolve-loop (transcript d acc)
    (if (eq (len transcript) 0) acc
      (dc-resolve-loop (tail transcript) d (dc-resolve-step acc (head transcript) d))))

  (defn dc-resolve (transcript d) (dc-resolve-loop transcript d (dc-absent)))

  ; dc-answered? — 1 when the question has ANY definite answer at all, 0 only
  ; when nothing was ever sent back. Note that an ack of `nothing` answers 1
  ; here: it is an answer.
  (defn dc-answered? (transcript d)
    (if (eq (dc-resolve transcript d) (dc-absent)) 0 1))

  ; ── the offer side: is my offer even ON this transcript? ─────────────────────

  (defn dc-has-offer-loop (transcript d)
    (if (eq (len transcript) 0) 0
      (if (eq (dc-frame-complete? (head transcript)) 0) (dc-has-offer-loop (tail transcript) d)
        (if (eq (dc-body-tag (head transcript)) (dc-tag-offer))
            (if (eq (dc-bytes-eq (dc-frame-declared-digest (head transcript)) d) 1) 1
                (dc-has-offer-loop (tail transcript) d))
            (dc-has-offer-loop (tail transcript) d)))))

  (defn dc-has-offer (transcript d) (dc-has-offer-loop transcript d))

  ; ── breach counting (axiom-4: breach is observable) ──────────────────────────
  ;
  ; A scan does not silently skip what did not cross the interface. It counts
  ; it, so "how many byte-runs on this transcript never passed the boundary?"
  ; has an answer.
  (defn dc-breach-count-loop (transcript acc)
    (if (eq (len transcript) 0) acc
      (dc-breach-count-loop (tail transcript)
        (if (eq (dc-frame-state (head transcript)) (dc-not-a-frame)) (add acc 1) acc))))

  (defn dc-breach-count (transcript) (dc-breach-count-loop transcript 0))

  (defn dc-incomplete-count-loop (transcript acc)
    (if (eq (len transcript) 0) acc
      (dc-incomplete-count-loop (tail transcript)
        (if (eq (dc-frame-complete? (head transcript)) 0) (add acc 1) acc))))

  (defn dc-incomplete-count (transcript) (dc-incomplete-count-loop transcript 0))

  ; ── how did this transcript END? (hushend) ───────────────────────────────────
  ;
  ; A close must carry evidence of why it closed. Three ends that a plain
  ; byte-stream renders identical are three different numbers here:
  ;    3 CLOSED  — the last frame is a valid CLOSE, and it NAMES the digest it
  ;                closed on and the reason it closed
  ;   -6 STOPPED — every frame is valid, and then the transcript simply ends.
  ;                No cut, no close. This is the honest "it just stopped".
  ;   -7 CUT     — the last frame is incomplete: the stream was severed
  ;                mid-write.
  ;
  ; This is the shape that answers "did that agent finish or die?" without any
  ; notification arriving. See the receipt for the named-but-unwired application.
  (defn dc-last (xs) (if (le (len xs) 1) (head xs) (dc-last (tail xs))))

  (defn dc-transcript-end (transcript)
    (if (eq (len transcript) 0) (dc-end-stopped)
      (if (eq (dc-frame-complete? (dc-last transcript)) 0) (dc-end-cut)
        (if (eq (dc-body-tag (dc-last transcript)) (dc-tag-close)) (dc-end-closed)
            (dc-end-stopped)))))

  ; dc-close-evidence — the reason a closed transcript gives. -1 when the
  ; transcript did not close, so "no reason" can never read as reason 0.
  (defn dc-close-evidence (transcript)
    (if (eq (dc-transcript-end transcript) (dc-end-closed))
        (dc-close-reason (dc-last transcript))
        -1))

  ; ── truncation, as a constructor ─────────────────────────────────────────────
  ; dc-cut — the stream severed after n bytes. Used by the band to walk every
  ; cut point of a real frame.
  (defn dc-cut (f n) (take n f))

  1)
